LABORATORY
ECG as noted above.  Chest x-ray shows normal cardiothoracic silhouette and clear lung fields.
IMPRESSION/REPORT/PLAN
#1 Chest pain syndrome
This could be due in part to coronary spasm in the setting of previously documented angiographically normal coronary arteries.  Some of her chest pain is no doubt noncardiac.  I do not think that functional testing will be of any benefit here.  I think she should remain on nitrates pre- and postoperatively and use nitroglycerin to treat episodes of chest pain.  As long as there is no electrocardiographic ST-segment deviation or features of hemodynamic compromise, I think a medical treatment course will be most appropriate.
#2 History of asthma
#3 Diabetes mellitus type-2
#4 Hypertension
#5 Orthopedic issues
#6 Cecal carcinoma with planned surgery next week
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

